{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"64fe2e82-d7b2-49c6-bd24-9007366ae683","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the CPU profiling profile. From inside the container:\n\n```bash\n# Install the tool (if not already present)\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# Find your app's PID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a 30-second CPU trace\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or convert to **speedscope** format:\n\n```bash\ndotnet-trace convert <file>.nettrace --format Speedscope\n```\n\n**Tips:**\n- If `dotnet` SDK isn't in the container, copy the tool binary in or use a sidecar/ephemeral container.\n- For lower-level OS+runtime insight, use **`dotnet-collect`** with `perf` (requires `SYS_PTRACE` / `privileged` capability).\n- `--duration` avoids forgetting to stop and generating huge files.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e6ddd36f-2b70-4cca-8855-88b34cca9c1b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code change task. I'll provide concise, practical guidance.","outputTokens":322,"requestId":"CB16:A3554:1D3B548:2062509:6A0525F0"},"id":"53976c70-5509-49c9-a26e-300d5f561423","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:31:38.275Z","parentId":"a1e90281-0bb0-4dbb-85f7-e2825e81273d"}
